 developing bodhicitta (altruistic awakening mind) and the antidote to self-grasping through the realization of the ultimate nature of reality: the correct view of emptiness. Chöd is regarded by many Tibetan Lamas as one of the most effective Buddhist practices for spiritual and social transformation. Jeffrey W. Cupchik details the significance of the complex, interwoven performative aspects of this meditative ritual and explains how its practice can bring about experiences of insight and inner transformation. In doing so, he undoes the notion of meditation being exclusively an experience of silence and stillness.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4aAsian Studies : Asian Religion and Philosophy. 4aAsian Studies : Asian Studies. 4aFilm, Visual Culture, and Performing Arts : Music. 4aReligion and Spirituality : Buddhism. 4aReligion and Spirituality : Tibetan Buddhism. 7aRELIGION / Buddhism / Rituals & Practice.2bisacsh1 aPencho Rabgey, M.S.C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRabgey, Pencho, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package 2024z978311149259940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978143846443540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438464435423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438464435/original  a978-3-11-149259-9  SUNY Press eBook Package 2024b2024  aGBV-deGruyter-alles